{"id":"2101.02297","submitter":"In Yong Park","authors":"I. Y. Park","title":"Cosmological constant as a finite temperature effect","comments":"24 (20+4) pages, comments added on potential implications for Hubble\n  tension and early dark energy, minor corrections, version to appear in IJMPA","journal-ref":"Int.J.Mod.Phys.A 37 (2022) 27, 2250173","doi":"10.1142/S0217751X22501731","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We reexamine the cosmological constant problem in a finite temperature setup\nand propose an intriguing possibility of carrying out perturbative analysis by\nemploying a renormalization scheme in which the renormalized Higgs mass (or\nresummed mass, to be more precise) is taken to be on the order of the CMB\ntemperature. Our proposal hinges on the fact that although the physical value\nof the cosmological constant does not depend on one's renormalization scheme,\nwhether or not a fine tuning is involved does. The cosmological constant\nproblem is avoided in the sense that the renormalization process no longer\nrequires finetuning. This is achieved essentially by renormalization\nscheme-independence of a physical quantity, which in turn is assured by bare\nperturbation theory. The proposal shifts the cosmological constant problem to a\npeculiarity of the consequent perturbation series for the Higgs mass (and other\nmassive sectors of the Standard Model); the peculiarity is interpreted as an\nindicator of new physics after the expected mathematical structure of the\nseries is scrutinized. Finite-temperature-induced complexification of the\neffective potential is observed and its interpretation is given. A consistency\ncheck in the cosmology context is suggested.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 6 Jan 2021 22:51:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 22 Jun 2021 14:15:25 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 13 Aug 2021 16:04:53 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sun, 26 D