{"id":"2101.02345","submitter":"Claude Gravel","authors":"Claude Gravel","title":"A generalization of the Von Neumann extractor","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT math.IT math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  An iterative randomness extraction algorithm which generalized the Von\nNeumann's extraction algorithm is detailed, analyzed and implemented in\nstandard C++. Given a sequence of independently and identically distributed\nbiased Bernoulli random variables, to extract randomness from the\naforementioned sequence pertains to produce a new sequence of independently and\nidentically distributed unbiased Bernoulli random variables. The iterative\nconstruction here is inspired from the work of Stout and Warren 1984 who\nmodified appropriately the tree of probabilities produced by recursively\nrepeating the Von Neumann's extraction algorithm. The correctness of the\niterative algorithm is proven. The number of biased Bernoulli random variables\nneeded to produce one unbiased instance is the complexity of interest. The\ncomplexity depends on the bias of the source. The expected complexity converges\ntoward 3.10220648... when the bias tends to 0 and diverges when the bias tends\nto 1/2. In addition to the expected complexity, some other results that concern\nthe limiting asymptotic construction, and that seem unnoticed in the literature\nso far, are proven.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 7 Jan 2021 03:09:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-01-08"}
